  "text": "Let Σ be a ranked alphabet. In this paper, we are interested in sets of finite Σ-labeled trees, or tree languages. It has been known since the 1960s [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] that the tree languages that are definable in monadic second order logic are exactly the so-called regular tree languages, that is, those accepted by bottom-up tree automata. Moreover, deterministic tree automata suffice to accept these languages, and each regular tree language admits a unique, minimal deterministic automaton. From the algebraic point of view, the set of all Σ-labeled trees can be viewed in a natural way as a (free) Σ-algebra, where Σ is now seen as a signature. Moreover, a deterministic bottom-up tree automaton can be identified with a finite Σ-algebra, with some distinguished (final) elements. Thus regular tree languages are also the recognizable subsets of the free Σ-algebra.",
